The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as tannins and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at important locations around the property in order to trace bat activity during the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also perform mobile studies using handheld detectors.
Experts' audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bats and what species do what.
A habitat map and a report will then be developed to produce a detailed landscape of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will be part of the decision on the measures to be taken, such as the construction of pastures and the best management of the forests of bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction that affects breeding sites and habitat containment.
Windmills and lighting may also pose a risk, the same as fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials and hu tax attacks.
The bats aren't actually blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road when they fly.
ATS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten competent experts who regularly carry out surveys, surveying breeding sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland’s first and only own flag mouse reserve on Three land property in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten flag mouse species.
