‘We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive'.
He emphasises the importance of mapping the bats before carrying out maintenance on a property since the inadvertent destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young people, and perhaps outsource an entire local population.
The bats are protected, and it is illegal to kill them, to harassment or to disturb them or to destroy their breeding places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish co-workers for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the audience to help in the work.
