Algal bloom update: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Commission on Fisheries and Animal Life (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spot-like blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County — suggesting reduced concentrations.
A flowering of red algae extends around 210 km along the coast, from north in Pinellas to south in Lee County.
There are spots discovered around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County have been reported in the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
No irritation was reported in the airways northwest of Florida during the last week.
